            <div class="reading-note" data-cid="20761300">
              <div class="short">
                
                  <span class="">After Muscovy annexed the Kazan Khanate there was no more obstacle for the new empire to conquer the rest of Siberia, including remnants of Mongol's Golden Horde, Khanate of Siberia and other north asian Tungusic people, until they met with Chinese empire in the Manchuria outskirt a century later. Why did the Mongols and Tatars collapse easily in front of Muscovy penetrations? Probably because fin...</span>
                <p class="pl">
                  <span class="">2012-08-31 11:30</span>
                  
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="all hidden" style="display:none" >
                After Muscovy annexed the Kazan Khanate there was no more obstacle for the new empire to conquer the rest of Siberia, including remnants of Mongol's Golden Horde, Khanate of Siberia and other north asian Tungusic people, until they met with Chinese empire in the Manchuria outskirt a century later. Why did the Mongols and Tatars collapse easily in front of Muscovy penetrations? Probably because finally history had turned into a tipping point where the settled civilizations started to overwhelm nomad states in central Eurasia once and for all. 
                  <div class="col-rec-con clearfix">
                    







