            <div class="reading-note" data-cid="20579775">
              <div class="short">
                
                  <span class="">While Ming China is unable to eliminate its northern threat by force, it was quite impressive that Ming China tricked the Mongols all the way by instigating their in-fighting and ruling them separately. The two powers enjoyed a mutually dependent relationship as silk-for-ponies border trades prospered. Two hundred years later Manchu China inherited this fragmentation strategy during its early Mong...</span>
                <p class="pl">
                  <span class="">2012-08-23 14:41</span>
                  
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="all hidden" style="display:none" >
                While Ming China is unable to eliminate its northern threat by force, it was quite impressive that Ming China tricked the Mongols all the way by instigating their in-fighting and ruling them separately. The two powers enjoyed a mutually dependent relationship as silk-for-ponies border trades prospered. Two hundred years later Manchu China inherited this fragmentation strategy during its early Mongolian borderland engagements. What Ming China left is absorbed, adapted and fine-tuned in Manchu China. 
                  <div class="col-rec-con clearfix">
                    







