            <div class="reading-note" data-cid="20630732">
              <div class="short">
                
                  <span class="">The Ming empire wanted to contain Jurchens the same way as they did to Mongols by controlling the grain/tea supplies Jurchens could get from borderland trade, only to find that Jurchens had nothing short to worry about as Manchuria itself was an abundant region. Jurchens rebelled against Ming rule after Ming took a unrealistic approach to try to cut off their tribal alliances, which was not as eff...</span>
                <p class="pl">
                  <span class="">2012-08-25 21:47</span>
                  
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="all hidden" style="display:none" >
                The Ming empire wanted to contain Jurchens the same way as they did to Mongols by controlling the grain/tea supplies Jurchens could get from borderland trade, only to find that Jurchens had nothing short to worry about as Manchuria itself was an abundant region. Jurchens rebelled against Ming rule after Ming took a unrealistic approach to try to cut off their tribal alliances, which was not as effective as dealing with Mongols because Jurchens had been united much more closely as a confederation than fifteen century Mongols. 
                  <div class="col-rec-con clearfix">
                    







